What Is Intent Decay and Why Should You Care
Intent decay describes the measurable decline in a prospect's buying signals over a defined period of time. It is the delta between where their intent activity was at its peak and where it stands today. Think of it as the digital equivalent of a prospect going cold, except now you can actually measure it in real time.

When a company is seriously evaluating a solution, they generate a consistent stream of intent signals. Multiple stakeholders research relevant topics. People visit review sites. Team members consume comparison content. There is a pattern of sustained, escalating digital activity that mirrors the internal urgency driving the evaluation.

When that urgency fades, for any number of reasons, the activity drops. Research intensity decreases. Engagement frequency falls. The signal cluster that once pointed clearly toward a purchase decision starts to dissipate. This is intent decay in action.

The critical question is whether your go-to-market team can see it happening in time to respond. Most cannot. They are relying on CRM data that reflects what a prospect told a sales rep, not what the prospect is actually doing online. By the time the sales rep notices something is off, the evaluation may have quietly moved on to a competitor, been shelved by a budget freeze, or simply lost internal momentum.

