How Intent Decay Manifests: The Warning Signs
Intent decay does not always look the same. It can present as a gradual decline, a sudden drop-off, or a shift in the topics a prospect is researching. Understanding the different patterns helps you calibrate your response.

The Gradual Fade

This is the most common pattern. An account that was generating consistent, strong intent signals across multiple topics begins to show declining activity week over week. Research intensity drops from daily to weekly to sporadic. The number of stakeholders generating signals decreases from several to one or two to none. This pattern often reflects an internal stall, a budget review, a change in priorities, or an evaluation that was quietly deprioritized.

The Competitor Pivot

In this pattern, intent signals do not disappear entirely but shift in their focus. An account that was researching your solution category begins generating signals around a specific competitor by name. This indicates the evaluation is still active but you may have fallen off the shortlist. This is urgent. Competitor pivot signals require immediate, high-value outreach before the window closes entirely.

The Sudden Drop

Sometimes intent decay is not gradual. A deal that was generating strong signals suddenly goes dark. This pattern often reflects an organizational trigger, a leadership change, a budget freeze, a merger, or an internal restructure. Understanding what caused the sudden drop is essential to knowing whether re-engagement is worthwhile or whether the deal should be removed from the active forecast.

The Topic Shift

An account that was researching purchase-oriented topics, pricing, implementation, integration specifications, begins researching general category-level content again. This regression in topic sophistication suggests the buying journey may have restarted rather than progressed, or that a new stakeholder has entered the evaluation and is starting from scratch.

